<HEADLINE> Drugs and Alcohol Behind Rise in Divorces in UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Drugs and alcohol addiction
among spouses are some of the new factors leading to divorces in
the United Arab Emirates (UAE), a local study has said.
</P>
<P>
Published as a book, "Reasons and Effects of Divorces" by the
Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs, the study revealed that
husbands' addiction to drugs and alcohol, their bad treatment for
their wives, their infidelity and polygamy topped the causes of
divorces in the country.
</P>
<P>
The divorce rate in the UAE has been rising steadily in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
Quoting reports released by the Ministry of Planning, the study
said that the actual divorce cases among a total number of 2.54
million local and expatriate inhabitants in the UAE increased from
1,876 in 1991 to 2,154 in 1996, while the actual divorce cases
among 784,043 UAE nationals increased from 1,149 in 1991 to 1,326
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, many divorced women have to depend
entirely on the monthly social grants provided by the government
and a lot of children become victims of the social problem.
</P>
<P>
The study proposed to set up family counseling centers in
addition to the introduction of stricter procedures for obtaining
a divorce.
</P>
<P>
It also called for the establishment of a security fund to look
after the children whose parents had remarried after a divorce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
