<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Cabinet Calls for PM's Special Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The federal cabinet of
Pakistan Saturday called for special security arrangements for
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif following attempts on his life earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
The call was made in a cabinet meeting chaired by the prime
minister and attended by federal ministers and ministers of state.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the media after the meeting, Information Minister
Mushahid Hussain said that the cabinet felt the prime minister was
the target of the bomb blast occurred on his route on January 3,
and directed the security agencies to beef up his security.
</P>
<P>
The attack on the prime minister was a conspiracy against
Pakistan and the democratic system in the country, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said the cabinet endorsed the imposition of the
Governor Rule in Sindh province and the establishment of military
courts to put an end to terrorism, lawlessness, kidnapping for
ransom and car lifting.
</P>
<P>
The military courts have been established for quick punishment
to the criminals and ensuring protection to the life and property
of the people, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The government's actions have yielded positive results and the
citizens of Karachi have taken sigh of relief," Hussain said.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet, he said, expressed satisfaction over the
government's efforts for the restoration of peace in Karachi and
called for continuation of these measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
