<HEADLINE> Roundup: E. African Countries Seek Common </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Li Jinqi)
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 23 (Xinhua) -- East African countries leaders
met at one-day summit discussing their common concern -- the
establishment of the East African Community (EAC) Friday in
northern Tanzanian town Arusha.
</P>
<P>
The presidents, Daniel arap Moi of Kenya, Benjamin Mkapa of
Tanzania and Yoweri Museveni of Uganda, reviewed their cooperation
in various fields over the past year and discussed issues on
regional cooperation in foreign affairs, economy, trade, security
and others.
</P>
<P>
The three heads of state especially reviewed the progress in
the draft treaty for the establishment of East African Community
which was made public last May, aiming at accelerating the pace of
regional integration.
</P>
<P>
So far, the draft treaty is being subjected to wide publicity
and public debate in the three countries and public views on any
of the provisions are invited. The public debate will end on
April 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
It is learnt that the treaty on the establishment of EAC is
scheduled to be completed and signed in July this year, thus
making East Africa a political and economic integration as a
common market and investment area, which the three leaders hope
will one day adopt a single currency like the European Community.
</P>
<P>
At the summit, the presidents discussed a memorandum on foreign
policy coordination, zero tariff rate, a mechanism to deal with
terrorism, admission of Rwanda to the community and other issues.
</P>
<P>
According to the memorandum signed by the foreign ministers,
the three east African states will take a common stand at the
international forum and will also assist each other in those
countries where they do not have embassies.
</P>
<P>
On the tariff rate issue, the leaders noted the progress on the
decision to adopt zero tariff rate on all products except an
agreed list of products, with effect from July 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The three presidents at the summit renewed their efforts for a
free trade zone in east Africa and for economic integration.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian President Mkapa said efforts should be made to "focus
on increasing the capacity of each country and increasing the
volume of inter- regional and international trade."
</P>
<P>
While vowing "the road to the East African Community is now
irreversible, " Kenyan President Moi called for a vigorous
publicity campaign to market the tourism and tap economic
potential in the region.
</P>
<P>
Uganda President Museveni also hailed the progress being made
to promote the region as an attractive investment destination.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that an east African passport will be launched
soon, which will facilitate easier travel within the region.
</P>
<P>
Each immigration authority in the three states has been
allocated 100, 000 such travel documents to be issued at the
equivalent of 10 U.S. Dollars each. Holders of the travel
document will be able to make multiple entries within the region
for a period of six months.
</P>
<P>
Over the past year or more, the three countries have also
fostered their cooperation in the fields of finance, military and
education.
</P>
<P>
The finance ministers of the three countries met in Nairobi
last April and worked out the "Long-Term Strategy of the East
African Development Bank" to further play the bank's role in the
process of regional economic integration and open up new services
focusing on financing the export of cotton and tea as well as the
export-oriented processing sectors.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, the bank has approved a total of 167
productive projects worth SDR71.09 million, including 70 ongoing
projects spread across the region.
</P>
<P>
The three countries have also enhanced their coordination and
cooperation in military affairs. Last June, they successfully
sponsored the first east African military manoeuvre in
northwestern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the countries appointed their respective
representatives to the Defense Affairs Unit at Arusha. The
setting up of the unit will promote collective and rational
utilization of military resources and training facilities, speedy
mobilization of peace-keeping and disaster management operations
in the region.
</P>
<P>
With the setting up of the University Council of East Africa,
there are also active academic exchanges among the universities
with mutual visits and research projects. Kenyatta University in
Kenya has conducted joint research on banana plant with other east
African universities.
</P>
<P>
The University Council of East Africa will this year arrange a
number of meetings on legal and science education, arts and social
sciences, engineering, veterinary education and exchange of
students.
</P>
<P>
East Africa with a combined population of some 84 million has
become an emerging market with vast opportunities for investors.
</P>
<P>
With relative stability in the three east African nations, it
is expected that they will achieve faster development in various
fields through joint efforts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
