<HEADLINE> African Countries Lift Sanctions Against Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Seven African countries
Saturday agreed to lift economic sanctions against Burundi's
military government to encourage peace negotiations aimed at
ending a five-year civil war, a report from Tanzania said.
</P>
<P>
"The regional leaders have unaniusly agreed that sanctions
should be suspended, not removed completely, but suspended,"
ugandan president Yoweri Museveni said at a summit in the
northern tanzanian town of arusha.
</P>
<P>
The summit was also attended by the leaders of Kenya,
Tanzania, Rwanda and Ethiopia and senior government officials
from the Democratic Republic of Congo and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were imposed by Burundi's neighbors after Major
Pierre Buyoya took power in a military coup in July, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Buyoya, now Burundi's president, addressed the summit and
pledged to push forward with efforts to bring a quick end to the
civil war between his ethnic Tutsi-led government and Hutu rebel
groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
