<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Raise VAT to 15 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' Finance Minister
Christodoulos Christodoulou announced here Saturday that Cyprus
plans to raise value-added tax (VAT) to 15 percent by the year
2002.
</P>
<P>
The intention was announced hours after the House of
Representatives (parliament) approved the three state
budgets: those of ordinary, development and relief fund.
</P>
<P>
According to the ordinary budget, estimated net revenue for
the 1999 is 1.11 billion Cyprus pounds (2.21 billion U.S. dollars)
and net expenditure is estimated at 1.71 billion pounds (3.41
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, the minister said the VAT
increase will be made in stages and the government will introduce
tax relief measures to favour the lower income class.
</P>
<P>
He said the VAT increase is necessary as part of Cyprus'
agreement with the European Union (EU) in its effort to obtain EU
accession.acquis communautaire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
