<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lifting of Burundi Embargo Will Ease Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The suspension of regional
economic sanctions against Burundi will be a major step in
restoring the central African nation's ability to meet its food
needs, said a news release issued by the Nairobi office of U.N.
World Food Program (WFP) available Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Seven African countries decided Saturday at a summit in the
northern Tanzanian town of Arusha to suspend sanctions imposed on
Burundi in August 1996, as long as peace talks between the
government and Hutu rebels continued to show progress.
</P>
<P>
Now that the sanctions have been suspended, WFP hopes it could
focus on its long-term development projects aimed to enable
Burundi to become more self-reliant in food supply, said the new
release.
</P>
<P>
The embargo drove up the prices of food and agricultural items
such as seeds, tools and fertilizers which had mostly hit the
small farmers, the U. N. food agency said.
</P>
<P>
"Many families could no longer afford to grow enough food or
buy supplies in the market, " said Thomas Yanga, WFP's
representative in Burundi. "This meant people were eating less
and becoming more vulnerable to malnutrition and disease."
</P>
<P>
In the past two and a half years, WFP has distributed over
67,000 tons of food to offset the impact of sanctions and the
civil war which has killed around 150,000 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
