<HEADLINE> Iraq Calls for Condemnation of U.S. Attack on It </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Iraq Saturday asked the upcoming
Arab foreign ministers' meeting to condemn U.S.-British military
strikes against it, a demand that seems unlikely to be satisfied.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf, who is here to
attend the meeting due Sunday, that Baghdad's "minimum" demand is
that the foreign ministers' meeting denounce the recent
U.S.-British attack on Iraq and help get the U.N. economic
sanctions on the country lifted.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf, who arrived here earlier in the day, made the
remarks after a meeting with Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries initially decided to convene the meeting on
December 30 to discuss the Iraqi issue after the attack, seeking
ways of restoring Arab solidarity and unity.
</P>
<P>
At the request of Kuwait and Saudi Arabia, the meeting was put
off to January 24 for better consultations and preparations.
</P>
<P>
Arab diplomatic sources in Cairo said that Iraq's demand would
unlikely be met as many Arab countries will not go so far as to
offend the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf denied reports that Iraq was beefing up military
force on the Iraqi-Kuwaiti border.
</P>
<P>
There are no Iraqi military build-up on the border and the
U.N. border inspectors and the Kuwaitis have denied the reports,
which he denounced as part of the efforts to garble and distort
the Arab and world public opinion.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain launched a four-day missile attack on Iraq
in mid-December for what the U.S. denounced as Baghdad's failure
to comply with the U.N. weapons inspections, which hold the key to
the lifting of the economic sanctions the U.N. Security Council
imposed on the country after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
