<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswanan Police Deny Detaining Namibian Reporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Botswanan police have
denied media reports of detaining two Namibian reporters, but
admitted that the reporters were questioned, Southern African
Broadcasting Association reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Kenneth Maphane, chief of Botswana's Criminal Investigations
Department, said Friday that the reporters were questioned for
filming Namibian opposition leaders in Botswana.
</P>
<P>
The Namibians, one reporter and one cameraman, are employees of
the Namibian Broadcasting Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Andreas Frai and Vincent Spiegel entered Botswana to cover the
trial of Misheck Muyongo, former president of the opposition
Democratic Turnhalle Alliance.
</P>
<P>
Muyongo and 92 others will be tried on Monday for crossing into
Botswana illegally, with weapons of war.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 Namibians have fled to Botswana since last year
when the authorities claimed to have uncovered Muyongo's plan to
pull the Caprivi Region out of the rest of Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Caprivi is a strip of land which separates Namibia from Angola,
Botswana and Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
