<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Warplanes Drop Bombs on Iraqi Air Defense Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. warplanes patrolling
southern no-fly zone in Iraq on Saturday dropped bombs on two
Iraqi surface-to-air missile sites after encourtering Iraqi MiG-21
fighters, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
The two U.S. F-14 Tomcats and two F/A-18 Hornets dropped
laser-guided bombs on two Iraqi surface-to-air missile systems
after encountering Iraqi MiG-21s "darting in and out" of the
off-limit airspace, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place at 1:15 a.m. EST (0615GMT). After
the bombing, the U.S. warplanes returned safely to the aircraft
carrier Carl Vinson in the Arabian Sea, they said.
</P>
<P>
The Americans "responded to a threat initiated by two Iraqi
MiG-21s flying south of 33rd parallel in Iraq and ground fire
from anti-aircraft artillery," said Lt. Col. Mike Milord, a
Pentagon spokesman.
</P>
<P>
At the White House, National Security Council spokesman David
Leavy said Saturday's incident would not alter U.S. resolve to
enforce the no-fly zones.
</P>
<P>
"As the president has made clear, we will continue to enforce
the no-fly zone vigorously and take appropriate action to
protect our aircraft and continue to contain the threat Saddam
(Hussein) poses to the region and international community,"
Leavy said.
</P>
<P>
It has been the ninth clashes between U.S. warplanes and Iraqi
air defense sites since mid-December bombing raids at Iraqi
targets by U.S. and British warplanes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
