<HEADLINE> Kremlin Refutes Constitutional Changes Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The Kremlin said Saturday that
there is no need for constitutional amendments on the president's
health as it is already"thoroughly reflected in the constituion".
</P>
<P>
The statement, by President Boris Yeltsin's spokesman Dmitry
Yakushkin, came after Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov's call early in
the day for such changes.
</P>
<P>
Yakushkin said Luzhkov's remarks "introduce unnecessary
nervousness and anxiety in the life of society, while there are
enough real problems in Russia without that," Itar-Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
"Everything seems to have been put in place (in Russia) now --
the Duma (lower house of parliament) works with the government;
the government with the Duma, and everyone has clear-cut tasks,"
Yakushkin said.
</P>
<P>
However, Luzhkov said the current constitution overlooks health
matters, calling for provisions on situations arising from
unexpected changes in the president's health.
</P>
<P>
The latest flurry of arguments surrounding Yeltsin's health
came after Yeltsin was rushed to the Central Clinical Hospital on
January 17 for acute gastric ulcer bleeding.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, 67, has been in and out of hospital several times in
the past year, prompting calls for him to step down to make room
for early presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
The Kremlin, however, has said repeatedly that Yeltsin is fully
capable of ruling the country as the "colossal factor of stability
in Russian society" and that he will serve out his term until
2000.
</P>
<P>
Yakushkin said statements like that made by Luzhkov "are full
of political intrigues."
</P>
<P>
Luzhkov, a presidential hopeful that often tops opinion polls,
said "the best thing for the president to do today would be to
honestly evaluate his condition and ability to work as the head of
state and perform his extremely intensive functions." 
</P>
</TEXT>
