<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maslyukov Warns Against Altering ABM Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian First Deputy Prime
Minister Yuri Maslyukov on Saturday reiterated Moscow's doubts
over the U.S.-proposed revisions to the Anti-ballistic Missile
Treaty (ABM).
</P>
<P>
A discussion on the future of the 1972 treaty has been under
way in the United States for several years, Maslyukov's spokesman
Anton Surikov quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said U.S. experts have failed to pay sufficient attention to
a possible reaction from the so-called third nuclear powers to
changes in the ABM.
</P>
<P>
A deployment of a limited ABM system could devalue their
nuclear forces, Maslyukov said. Therefore, some of these countries
could build up their strategic offensive weapons, primarily
inter-continental ballistic missiles with multiple warheads, as "a
cheapest form of response," he added.
</P>
<P>
Maslyukov warned that While Russia and the United States plan
to reduce their strategic offensive weapons under the START II and
future START III treaties, careless steps in revising the ABM
could provoke reverse steps by the third nuclear powers, Interfax
reported.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Washington "exaggerates and excessively
dramatizes" the threat from what it calls "rouge countries"
notably Iran, Iraq, and Libya, he said.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear threat from third world countries should be dealt
with by stepping up control of the export of nuclear arms
technologies and the means for their delivery, Maslyukov said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
