<HEADLINE> Palestinian Official Stresses National Right to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians stressed on
Saturday that declaring an independent Palestinian state on May 4
is the right for them acquired by virtue of agreements signed with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Minister of Planning and International Cooperation
Nabil Shaath said May 4 should not be dealt with as an ordinary
day, adding that it is "a historic and vital day," on which the
Palestinian right should be reserved and maintained.
</P>
<P>
Shaath made the remarks at a press conference held after a
meeting between Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat in Egypt's Sinai resort of Sharm el-Sheikh,
about 380 kilometers southeast of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
He termed as "important as usual" the meeting between Mubarak
and Arafat, during which he said the Egyptian president expressed
support for the Palestinians to grasp all chances so as not to
fritter away their rights.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has announced he will declare the Palestinian state on
May 4 according to the Oslo accord signed with Israel in 1993. But
the Jewish state opposes the plan, threatening to take unilateral
actions against the possible step.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Israel's threat to annex occupied Palestinian
lands if the Palestinian state is declared, Shaath said "it is not
these threats which will affect our decisions or the way by which
we take them."
</P>
<P>
"We should not fear the threats of a state that illegally
occupies others' lands," he said, adding that the Palestinians'
stances are "based on righteousness."
</P>
<P>
Arafat, a frequent visitor to Egypt for consultations with
Mubarak on the Mideast peace process, arrived in the Red Sea
resort earlier in the day for a one-day visit, Egypt's Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, Arafat briefed Mubarak on the deadlock in
the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks due to Israel's freeze of the
implementation of the Wye accord signed last October in
Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
