<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Accuses U.S. of Violating START I </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 23 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Russian defense
official on Saturday accused the United States of violating the
first Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty (START I).
</P>
<P>
Leonid Ivashov, head of the Russian Defense Ministry's
department of international cooperation, told the Krasnaya Zvezda
newspaper that Washington's breaches of START I would further
hamper the ratification of the START II treaty in the State Duma,
or lower house of the Russian parliament.
</P>
<P>
He said Moscow's major concern is over submarine-based
ballistic missiles Trident, intercontinental ballistic missiles MX
and heavy bombers B-1B, Itar-Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
Ivashov said the U.S., is pursuing flight tests of Trident
missiles for carrying more warheads than allowed by the START I
treaty.
</P>
<P>
The START I treaty, signed in Moscow in July 1991 by then
Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev and U.S. President George Bush,
calls for reducing the two sides' strategic offensive arms by
approximately 30 percent in three phases in seven years.
</P>
<P>
Ivashov said Russian wants Washington's "meticulous and
reciprocal" compliance to the START I treaty.
</P>
<P>
He said keeping the U.S. violations going would provide
Washington with an opportunity to build up unilateral military
advantages that promise to undermine both START I and START II.
</P>
<P>
START II, signed in Moscow by Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and Bush, calls for both sides to halve their nuclear warheads
each to 3,000-3,500 within a decade.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. senate ratified the START II on January 26, 1996, and
the Russian State Duma appeared ready to approve it late last
year, but U.S.-led airstrikes against Iraq and Washington's
sanctions against three Russian institutes for allegedly providing
nuclear and missile knowhow to Iran fueled anti-U.S. sentiments,
almost choking any chance of the START II's ratification in the
Duma in the near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
