<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Defense Minister Dismissed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu fired Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, who is accused
of not supporting the policy of the government.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said in a statement that Mordechai has been driven by
his personal ambition and not fully supported the policies of the
government.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Mordechai, Netanyahu said "you will no longer be
able to serve as Defense Minister in the government headed by
Likud. Your tenure will officially come to an end 48 hours after
this letter is delivered to you."
</P>
<P>
"I intend to appoint a replacement for you immediately,
someone loyal to Likud principles and ideology, who is ready to
serve the state of Israel loyally, without giving preference to
his personal interests," Netanyahu said in his letter.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who is campaigning for the early general elections
scheduled for May, is reportedly to have asked Moshe Arense, his
old friend, to replace Mordechai and he got a positive answer.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Netanyahu cited reasons why he has to remove
the Defense Minister from office, saying Mordechai was "conducting
negotiations with the opposition parties in order to topple the
Likud government."
</P>
<P>
"Elected to the Knesset (parliament) by Likud and appointed
Minister of Defense by a Likud Prime Minister, you have in the
past weeks nevertheless conducted negotiations with opposition
parties whose goal is to bring down the Likud government,"
Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Mordechai had asked him to promise in a written
form to guarantee the position as defense minister in a
government headed by Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said in the letter that he could not make such
promise to Mordechai because that could go against the Likud"s
principles.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also accused Mordechai for not following the Likud
way which leads to security, to safeguarding Israel and Jerusalem
and to negotiations with the Palestinians on reciprocity.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that Mordechai's departure from the
government would cause damage to the Likud. But it is also
difficult for Netanyahu to keep Mordechai in the Likud as the
latter had decided to join other parties in running the May
elections.
</P>
<P>
During the last two weeks, Mordechai held secret meetings
with former chief of staff Amnon Lipkin-Shahak and intended to
join his centrist party to run the upcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Mordechai refused to offer his candidacy
for the Likud Knesset list, indicating he would leave the
party soon.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai has accused Netanyahu for running the government
personally and sometimes even rejected listening the proposals
and suggestions provided by the military.

23/01/99 19:58 GMT

NNNN
04:04 04:05 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
