<HEADLINE> Sudanese Government Denies Prolonging Ceasefire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Foreign Minister
Mustafa Osman Ismail denied Saturday reports that the government
has prolonged the ceasefire with rebels in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese News Agency reported that Ismail denied reaching
agreement with southern rebels over a United Nations request to
extend the ceasefire in the famine-ravaged Bahr al-Ghazal province
and upper Nile ares.
</P>
<P>
Ismail said that such issue is to be discussed during the
forthcoming visit by the Inter-Governmental Authority on
Development (IGAD) ministerial delegation to Khartoum from January
23 to 26.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Sudanese government aims to achieve overall
ceasefire and revitalize the blocked peace talks with the rebel
Garang movement since October 1997 under the IGAD auspices.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on a U.S. State Department statement that urged the
Sudanese government to extend the ceasefire, Ismail said no
contacts or debates were conducted with the U.S. over the issue.
</P>
<P>
A previous extension of ceasefire in south Sudan was announced
by the government last July to help deliver relief aids to the
famine-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
The predominantly Christian and animist southerners took up arms
in 1983 against the Muslim controlled north for increased autonomy.
</P>
<P>
The IGAD partner states, namely Canada, Britain, Italy and the
Netherlands, have been making intensive mediation to end the
16-year civil war, which has claimed the lives of 1.5 million
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
