<HEADLINE> Israeli Sacked Minister Accuses PM of Telling Lies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January (Xinhua) -- Israeli sacked Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai Saturday said that Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu said nothing but lies in the letter of dismissal to him.
</P>
<P>
He said that just contrary to the accusations by Netanyahu, he
was loyal to the country, the Israeli people, the Israeli
military and the Likud party.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said that it was Netanyahu who run the government
against the will of the Israeli people, according to the Israel
Radio just hours after Netanyahu announced his decision to fire
the minister.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Netanyahu has no capability for running
the government and should be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said in a statement earlier that he dismissed
Mordechai because the minister had been driven by personal
ambition and not fully supported the policies of the government.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that he has to remove the defense minister from
office because Mordechai was "conducting negotiations with the
opposition parties in order to topple the Likud government."
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Mordechai, Netanyahu said "you will no longer be
able to serve as defense minister in the government headed by
Likud. Your tenure will officially come to an end 48 hours after
this letter is delivered to you."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who is campaigning for the early general elections
scheduled for May, is reportedly to have asked Moshe Arens, his
old friend, to replace Mordechai and he got a positive answer.
</P>
<P>
Arens, Likud's former defense minister and foreign minister,
said Saturday evening that he will make final decision next
Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, Arens accused Netanyahu for leading the Likud into a
mess recently. Arens announced on January 11 that he would run
for Likud's leadership when the party central committee meet
later this month.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that Mordechai's departure from the
government would cause damage to the Likud. But it is also
difficult for Netanyahu to keep Mordechai in the Likud as the
latter had decided to join other parties in running the May
elections.
</P>
<P>
During the last two weeks, Mordechai held secret meetings
with former chief of staff Amnon Lipkin-Shahak and intended to
join his centrist party to run the upcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Mordechai refused to offer his candidacy
for the Likud Knesset list, indicating he would leave the
party soon.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai has accused Netanyahu for running the government
personally and sometimes even rejected listening the proposals
and suggestions provided by the military.

