<HEADLINE> Yemen Optimistic Over Arab Reconciliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Yemeni Foreign Minister
Abdul Qader Ba-Jammal on Saturday expressed optimism over the
realization of Arab reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Yemen is "optimistic" about Arab reconciliation, considering
the ongoing extensive talks, Ba-Jammal told reporters after a
meeting with his Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa.
</P>
<P>
"We should not lose hope in achieving Arab reconciliation," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait split the Arab world. Till now,
Kuwait and Saudi Arabia have not forgiven the Iraqi government,
and Arab countries have yet to reach a unified stance on the Iraqi
issue.
</P>
<P>
Ba-Jammal, also Yemen's deputy prime minister, arrived here
earlier in the day for the Sunday meeting of Arab foreign
ministers, which is to discuss the Iraqi issue after a recent
military attack by the United States and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Following the U.S.-British mid-December attack on Iraq, Yemen
called for an Arab summit aimed at reaching a unified stand toward
the Iraqi issue, seeking Arab reconciliation and solidarity.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries later decided to hold the foreign ministers
meeting to discuss the Iraqi issue and the possibility of a summit.
</P>
<P>
Yemen still favors a pan-Arab summit in a bid to bring Arab
countries close through frank and open talks, Ba-Jammal said,
stressing that "this is the road we should take at any price to
achieve Arab solidarity."
</P>
<P>
He maintained that the climate is "optimistic" despite
complications in the Arab world, which he described as solvable.
</P>
<P>
"All the parties are working for making Sunday's meeting a
success," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
