<HEADLINE> Syrian FM Criticizes U.S.-British Attack on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq
al-Sharaa Sunday criticized the United States and Britain for
launching military strikes against Iraq last month.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of an Arab foreign ministers'
meeting here, al-Sharaa denounced the U.S.-British attack as "an
aggression on Iraq regardless of international legitimacy and the
U.N. Security Council."
</P>
<P>
Al-Sharaa, who chaired the session, said the use of force "has
not achieved any clear objective except increasing the sufferings
of the Iraqi people and endangering the regional stability and
security."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain launched four-day air strikes against Iraq
in mid-December for what the U.S. denounced as Baghdad's failure
to comply with the U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The Arab foreign ministers' meeting, originally scheduled in
December and later postponed, is aimed at seeking a unified stance
on Iraq. Eighteen Arab foreign ministers and four representatives
to the Arab League took part in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sharaa termed the convocation of the meeting an achievement,
calling on the foreign ministers to exert "every possible effort
to restore the minimum level of Arab solidarity."
</P>
<P>
He urged the Arab countries to make serious efforts to get the
U.N. trade embargo on Iraq lifted, calling for full arab
solidarity with the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions, imposed by the U.N. Security Council on Iraq
after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait, will not be lifted until the
U.N. arms inspectors certify that Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction have been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's invasion of Kuwait split the Arab world into pro- and
anti-Iraqi camps. The Arab countries are still divided over
stances on Iraq. Till now, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia have not
forgiven Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
