<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Does Not Rule Out Sending Ground Troops to Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, January 24 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder on Saturday did not rule out the possibility that
German ground troops would take part in the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization's (NATO) military intervention in the troubled
Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said in an interview with the Focus magazine that
military pressure is needed on Yugoslavia to prevent an increase
in violence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We have to talk to our partners about how we can avoid a
situation similar to what happened in Bosnia," Schroeder
said,"The intervention there came only after tens of thousands
were killed."
</P>
<P>
"We can hardly believe the policies of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic any more," Schroeder added, "Everyone has to
know that a military intervention can no longer be ruled out."
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said he opposes isolated air strikes because it
"won't improve the lot of people of Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
He also argued that it is wrong that Germany could not send
troops to places where Hitler's Nazi troops once invaded during
World War II.
</P>
<P>
"Just because we have stains in history, we need to go there
with our partners to stop the killings going on," he said.
</P>
<P>
Situation in Kosovo has been slightly eased since Belgrade
froze the expulsion of William Walker as head of the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe's (OSCE) Kosovo
Verification Mission.
</P>
<P>
However, NATO sources say its forces are still ready to launch
air strikes at Yugoslav military targets and to send ground
troops after the attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
