<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Delegation to Visit Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 24 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. delegation will visit
Afghanistan Monday for talks with the Taliban on humanitarian
assistance and conditions for the return of U.N. international
staff to the country.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, to be led by the Islamabad-based Coordinator
for Afghanistan, Erick De Mul, will hold talks with the Afghan
militia's supreme leader Mulla Mohammad Omar in the southern city
of Kandahar, official sources said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and foreign non-government organizations pulled out
their international staff from Kabul after an Italian U.N. worker
was shot dead in the Afghan capital by an angry mob on August 21,
last year.
</P>
<P>
The controversy between the Taliban and the U.N. over the
return of international staff badly affect some 70 thousand widows
and orphans in Kabul, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban and the U.N. signed a "security agreement" in
Islamabad on October 23, 1998, listing several conditions for the
return of international staff to the war-ravaged country.
</P>
<P>
The agreement had made the Taliban bound to provide full
protection to the U.N. staff and premises and investigate into the
killing of three U.N. officials in Kabul and the eastern city of
Jalalabad last year.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. wants those responsible for the murders to be arrested
and punished before it sends the international staff back to
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban said that they had arrested two suspected Pakistani
nationals in connection with the attack on the U.N. official in
Kabul who are being questioned in the militia's headquarters of
Kandahar.
</P>
<P>
However, the Pakistanis have pleaded not guilty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
