<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-24 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Erekat Urges to Move Peace Process Forward </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian side will
continue to move the peace process forward and the international
community must find compulsory mechanisms to force Israeli
government to implement the signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
The statement was made by Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb
Erekat during an interview with the Voice of Palestine on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The collapse of the peace process on the Palestinian-Israeli
track means catastrophes to the region and difficulties for the
entire world," Erekat warned.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government stopped implementing the Wye peace
accord last December citing accusations that the Palestinian side
has not fulfilled its commitments, bringing peace process to a
standstill once again.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the upcoming May elections in Israel will also
affect the peace process, not only in the non-implementation of
the accords, but also pertaining to attempts to gain votes by the
Israeli government from Israeli right wing and extremists who
oppose the agreements signed in Oslo, Madrid and Wye, Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
All of that will be reflected into impacts on grounds, which
means more settlement activities, more land confiscations and more
destructions to the peace process, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The United States should initiate to find compulsory mechanisms
for implementing the peace process, as long as it admits that the
Palestinian side has implemented its commitments of peace, he
said.
</P>
<P>
On the question of whether the Palestinian side will declare an
independent state on May 4 when the five-year interim period of
Oslo ends, Erekat said this is not a Palestinian day and was not
invented by the Palestinians - it was a result of understanding
and agreement between both the Palestinian and Israeli parties.
</P>
<P>
"The date 4 of May appeared for the first time in the Wye
River Memorandum which was signed by Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu himself," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, it is a day which has international legitimacy by
all who participated in signing the agreement. Consequently, the
Palestinian leadership can not postpone this date for even an hour
in announcing an independent palestinian state," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
