<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- An additional 30 billion U.S. dollars of
investments are in urgent need to develop the Mideast
telecommunications sector, which can yield 25 billion dollars in
annual profits for the investors, the Gulf News daily reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Recent research has shown that the telecommunications
industry worldwide was worth over 760 billion dollars at the end
of 1998, compared with 520 dollars in the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The forecast for 1999 is estimated to exceed a staggering 980
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Experts expected that the Gulf countries' official
spending to hit a decade-low of less than 75 billion dollars this
year in an effort to step up economic reforms aimed at boosting
growth and slashing budget deficits.
</P>
<P>
Banking sources of the Gulf Cooperation Council said the
the figure came as a result of expected lower oil prices this
year, the Arabic daily Alalam Alyoum reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The total official spending of Gulf states in 1998 was over 85
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq is considering modernizing its domestic
telephone network to macth its neighboring countries which have
achieved major development in this field through extending the
telecommunication grids and making use of hi-tech digital systems.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic daily Al-Haiyat reported Sunday that the Iraqi
General Telecommunications and Mail Company announced Friday that
it is to clinch a deal with the French Phone and Electronic Systems
company, Alctil, to renovate the Iraqi telephone network.
</P>
<P>
The transaction is expected to hit 1 to 2 billion dollars over
the three coming years.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A major Egyptian oil refinery with an estimated cost of
1.2 billion dollars will go into operation by the end of 2000, Oil
Minister Hamdi el-Banbi said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The refinery, located in the free zone in the Mediterranean
port city of Alexandria, is designed to produce an annual 5
million tonnes of oil products, which will be processed in
accordance with international standards for environmental
protection.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey permitted a foreign capital worth 1.64
billion U.S. dollars to be realized in 1998, a Turkish offical
data says.
</P>
<P>
According to the data release by the Undersecretariat of
Treasury here on Sunday, the Netherlands took the biggest share
with 352.05 million dollars, Germany followed as the second with
329.9 million dollars while the United States came the third with
297.2 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
