<HEADLINE> China to Tighten Financial Supervision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China
(PBOC), China's central bank, announced at its annual working
conference which ended recently that it will continue to tighten
financial supervision and prevent financial risks this year to
ensure the country's steady economic development.
</P>
<P>
Following a decision by the State Council, the PBOC carried
out a significant reform of its administrative system last year
by establishing nine regional branches to replace its original 31
branches in provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities.
</P>
<P>
The PBOC will play an important role in maintaining social
stability this year by further stepping up its supervision of the
financial sector, making efforts to maintain balanced
international payments, and preventing financial risks.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, the PBOC will establish an early warning
system for financial risk management which will include a
financial supervision responsibility system and solutions to the
problem of payment risks faced by small financial organizations.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will also be made to improve the central bank's
services and financial supervision capability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
