<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-24 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Chief Calls for Unified Arab Stance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General
Esmat Abdel-Meguid called on Arab countries here on Sunday to
reach a unified stance to grapple with "challenges and dangers at
the regional and international levels."
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of a meeting of Arab foreign
ministers on the Iraqi impasse, which started earlier in the day,
Abdel-Meguid also urged Arab countries to handle the problem
"through dialogue, understanding and hard work".
</P>
<P>
"This will lead to consolidating Arab capabilities and building
sound and stable inter-Arab relations based on frankness and
reconciliation," he said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, originally scheduled in December but later
postponed for disagreements in the Arab world, has been intended
to formulate a common stand on the Iraqi issue following the
U.S.-British airstrikes on December 16-19.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will also try to seek the restoration of Arab
reconciliation and solidarity
</P>
<P>
Terming the meeting as "the first step" on the way to improving
the Arab situation, Abdel-Meguid voiced hope that it will produce
substantial results to promote the Arab ambitions "in closing
ranks and restoring solidarity."
</P>
<P>
"Our national responsibility requires us to bring Iraq back to
the Arab family in view of Baghdad's compliance with the U.N.
Security Council resolutions related to the (1990) Gulf crisis,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990 split the Arab world. Till
now, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia have not forgiven Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed sweeping economic sanctions
on Iraq after its invasion of Kuwait in 1990. The sanctions will
not be lifted until Iraq's weapons of mass destruction have been
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Chairing the opening session of the foreign ministers' meeting,
Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Sharaa criticized the
U.S.-British attack on Iraq. He denounced it as "sheer aggression
on Iraq regardless of the international legitimacy and
U.N. resolutions."
</P>
<P>
He said the foreign ministers were gathering to demand the
lifting of the sanctions and express solidarity with the Iraqi
people.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen Arab foreign ministers and four permanent
representatives to the Arab League are attending the meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
