<HEADLINE> China to Invest Over 11 Billion Yuan in Civil Aviation This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) China plans to pour 11.1 billion
yuan into the civil aviation sector this year, according to Liu
Jianfeng, director of the General Administration of Civil
Aviation of China.
</P>
<P>
 Some 6.2 billion yuan will be invested in infrastructure
construction, three billion in technical upgrading, and 1.94
billion yuan will be in the form of loans for aircraft purchases.
</P>
<P>
 Liu said this money will be mainly used for projects which
will be put into operation this year, including the Beijing
Capital Airport, the Shanghai Pudong Airport and the Haikou
Meilan Airport located in Haikou, the capital of Hainan Province,
the country's largest special economic zone.
</P>
<P>
 The expansion project at the Kunming Wujiaba Airport in the
capital of southwest China's Yunnan province will be completed on
schedule, in time to welcome the 99' World Horticultural
Exhibition which will be held in Kunming, Liu noted.
</P>
<P>
 The official added that construction of the New Baiyun
Airport in Guangzhou will also begin as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
 Current statistics show that China's civil aviation sector
invested 23.64 billion yuan in fixed assets in 1998, an increase
of 6.5 percent on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
 Last year also saw progress in civil-aviation infrastructure
construction. For example, the expansion project at the Beijing
Capital Airport and the infrastructure project at the Shanghai
Pudong Airport were both completed successfully. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
