<HEADLINE> Mandela Cancels Visit To Uganda Due to Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 24 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela has cancelled his planned visit to Uganda in view
of the recent violence in Richmond, KwaZulu-Natal.
</P>
<P>
"In view of the events in Richmond, the president thought he
should delay his overseas trip for a few days. This means that he
will not go to Uganda," South African Press Association quoted
Foreign Ministry spokesman Marco Boni as saying Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Boni said Mandela had spoken to Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni who said he understood the situation.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo and Defense Minister
Joe Modise will lead a delegation to Uganda where they will sign
an investment promotion agreement.
</P>
<P>
They will also open a new sports stadium there which is being
named after Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, however, still planned to visit Germany and
Switzerland next week.
</P>
<P>
Boni did not say whether Mandela would visit Richmond, where
United Democratic Movement General Secretary, Sifiso Nkabinde, was
assassinated Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
Eleven people were killed Saturday night in what is believed to
be a revenge attack for Nkabinde's death. 
</P>
</TEXT>
