<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China '99 International Senior Citizens Forum Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The China's '99 International
Senior Citizens Forum opened here today in the Great Hall of the
People.
</P>
<P>
The forum aims at boosting the development of scientific
research and other social activity related to the aging po
pulation, in response to the International Year of Senior
Citizens initiated by the United Nations General Assembly, said
Peng Peiyun, vice chairman of National People's Congress Standing
Committee and director of the Chinese Population Society.
</P>
<P>
Co-sponsored by the Chinese Population Society and the Jintai
commercial group, the forum is welcoming 80 experts and officials
from the fields of population studies, economics, sociology and
medicine who will discuss the impact of the aging process on the
economy, the establishment of a pension system, the relationship
between the aging process and sustainable development and related
topics.
</P>
<P>
The seminars are all being held under the banner of "Towards a
Society for All Ages" designated by the United Nations for this
year.
</P>
<P>
Peng said the UN has reminded the world of the aging process
in 20th century as a challenge new to mankind.
</P>
<P>
Along with their previous contributions, our senior citizens
still offer their strength to society and deserve respect nation
wide, Peng stressed.
</P>
<P>
Respect for the elderly is regarded as a basic ethic in
Chinese culture, and "a society for all ages" means not only that
senior citizens should share in the nation's wealth, but that
they also should be respected as equal members of society
regardless of their age, added Peng.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
