<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-24 12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian President Urges Healthy Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami Sunday called for unity among political parties and
groups in order to present a "healthy competition" in the country.
</P>
<P>
"This competition must be coupled with ethical, Islamic and
humane yardsticks and all must prove their enthusiasm in
practice," Khatami said at the opening session of a three-day
gathering on "Islamic Councils and People's Participation."
</P>
<P>
He called on all political groups and factions to participate
in the coming elections of city and village councils starting on
February 23, the first since the Islamic revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
"The councils elections must be turned into a field for
displaying our national will and determination and I expect all
the factions and groups to get united in this arena to ensure
people's presence and sovereignty," he said.
</P>
<P>
Khatami's government has promised to cede some authorities and
rights to the people by holding the local elections to choose
mayors and village chiefs.
</P>
<P>
He also underlined the need to recognize the differences of
styles and tastes of various political factions and individuals.
</P>
<P>
"We must recognize the differences and should not let
competition turn into confrontation," he noted, adding that "the
left, the right, the centralist, all these classifications must
develop."
</P>
<P>
Khatami stressed the importance of people's participation in
the country's political, economic and social affairs, terming it
one of the most important slogans of the government.
</P>
<P>
"To be fair, on the average, the people's (political) maturity
is higher than that of the institutions, organs and those who
claim to be social teachers," he said.
</P>
<P>
Iran's conservative and moderate factions have been engaged in
a political wrangling in recent month following the revelation of
the involvement of the country's intelligence agents in political
killings of several dissidents.
</P>
<P>
An Iranian opposition leader, his wife and at least three other
dissident writers were murdered by a group of agents of the
Intelligence Ministry late last year.
</P>
<P>
The moderates called for a fundamental change in the
Intelligence Ministry after it admitted the involvement while the
conservatives accused Khatami's supporter of being behind the
murders.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here said that the two rival factions
intended to use the murder issue to defame the other prior to the
coming local elections.
</P>
<P>
Khatami has expressed regret over the political killings and
promised to firmly deal with the issue "as a matter of national
security and in order to create mutual confidence."
</P>
<P>
"This source of corruption and the roots of corruption in the
society in general, must be eliminated and we hope that the
society will move forward with more vigor," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
