<HEADLINE> Oil Smuggler Fined, Sentenced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGDONG, January 24 (Xinhua) -- An oil refinery deputy
director in South China's Guangdong Province who took part in the
largest oil-smuggling scheme ever was sentenced to eight years in
prison today and fined 15 million yuan (1.8 million U.S. dollars)
by a local court.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Manzhang, deputy director of the Fuxing Oil Refinery in
the city of Zhongshan in Guangdong, was found guilty of
collaborating with Hong Kong and Singapore businessmen and two
Cantonese in smuggling 90,000 tons of refined oil into China on
April 3 last year.
</P>
<P>
The two Cantonese, Guo Zaifu and Guo Gangfu, nicknamed "Oil
Kings of Guangdong," are still at large.
</P>
<P>
A foreign liner carrying the smuggled goods was also seized by
customs officials and police last April 3. The oil was bought
from a Singapore company for the price of 106.81 U.S. dollars a
ton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
