<HEADLINE> Kenyan President to Mediate Ethiopian-Eritrean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Moi left Nairobi with a group of advisors only 16 hours after
returning from a summit with Tanzanian and Ugandan presidents in
northern Tanzanian city Arusha, the Kenya radio reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the Kenyan government sources, the mission was
important for Africa, and Moi will urge Eritrea President Isayas
Afewerki to avoid a new confrontation with Ethiopia over the
border dispute.
</P>
<P>
No more details of Moi's trip to Eritrea was given by the
sources.
</P>
<P>
Kenya, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Djibouti and Somalia are members of
the Inter- Government Authority for Development which links
countries in the Horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
United Nation Security Council members expressed concern Friday
over a continuing military buildup along the 960-km border of the
two countries, which posed a threat for renewed fighting over
contested border areas after an armed conflict last May.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea became Africa's newest independent state in 1993 when
it broke away from Ethiopia with Ethiopia's agreement. Relations
between the two states broke down in 1998 with each accusing the
other of invading their common border.  
</P>
