<HEADLINE> Full-Steam Ahead for Sydney Olympics: Australian Acting PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Australian federal
government Sunday expressed "full confidence" in the Sydney
Olympics bidding process and said it was "full-steam ahead" for
the year 2000 Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
The comments by Acting Prime Minister Tim Fischer follow fears
that the Sydney Olympics could be under threat due to the
burgeoning Olympic bribery scandal.
</P>
<P>
Saturday Australian Olympic Committee President John Coates
said he sensed Sydney's chances of hosting the 2000 Olympics were
slipping away before he pledged extra payments to two African IOC
members on the eve of the 1993 vote.
</P>
<P>
But Acting Prime Minister Tim Fischer was Sunday upbeat about
the future of the event.
</P>
<P>
"It is full steam ahead for the 2000 Sydney Olympics," he said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"I absolutely believe they will be held in Sydney and they
will be successful, boosting Australian tourism nationwide.
</P>
<P>
"The saga over Olympic site selection has developed under the
overview of J. A. Samaranch, and clearly there will be procedural
changes in the new millennium."
</P>
<P>
Fischer also voiced support for the Games organizers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
