<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Plans to Phase Out Auto-rickshaws in Dhaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is
planning to phase out two-stroke-engine vehicles from Dhaka city
by the year 2001 instead of 2003, in a bid to protect the
environment, the Independent daily newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the government decided to phase out the
auto-rickshaws by 2003, but considering the deteriorating air
pollution, "we want to do it earlier and complete the job by
2001," an authoritative source in the Ministry of Environment and
Forest was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The motor vehicles, mainly auto-rickshaws, which pollute the
city air heavily, will be phased out under a project to be funded
by the World Bank (WB), he said.
</P>
<P>
A proposal for the purpose is being prepared by the ministry
for approval by the higher authorities of the government.
</P>
<P>
The WB will provide five million U.S. dollars for the
three-year project to be implemented from the middle of this year
to make the city free of air pollution.
</P>
<P>
Comprehensive measures will be taken under the project to
combat the growing air pollution in the capital city inhabited by
over nine million people.
</P>
<P>
Authorities concerned are preparing a detailed work plan under
the project which will lay stress on controlling the emission of
black smoke by motor vehicles, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, the report did not mention how many auto-rickshaws now
plying in the streets and the total cost of the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
