<HEADLINE> IOC to Study Salt Lake Scandal Investigation Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, Switzerland, January 24 ( Xinhua) -- The Executive
Board of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) will study the
report on Sunday and decide whether to recommend that members who
broke the rules on receiving gifts should be thrown out of the
organization.
</P>
<P>
Six of the 13 members involved in the Salt Lake City bribery
scandal were questioned by an investigating committee on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 13 people have been accused of taking goods and services
worth 600,000 U.S. dollars from Salt Lake when it won the right
to host the 2002 Winter Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
According to IOC rules, members are not allowed to accept
gifts worth more than 150 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Two of the 13, Finland's Pirjo Haggman and Libya's Bashir
Mohamed Attarabulsi, announced their resignation before
Saturday's meeting. But the IOC refused to name the other members
involved in the scandal.
</P>
<P>
"All the 13 members have submitted written explanations. The
commission met with six members. Those who did not appear have
been advised that the study of their cases will be based on the
written explanations," said IOC Spokesman Franklin
Servan-Schreiber. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
