<HEADLINE> Arab FMs Meet for Unified Stance on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from 16 Arab
states met here Sunday in a bid to reach a unified stance on the
Iraqi issue.
</P>
<P>
The developments of the Iraqi situation after the mid-December
U.S.-British attack on the country and U.N. sanctions on Iraq top
the agenda of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain launched four-day air strikes against Iraq
last month for what the U.S. denounced as Baghdad's failure to
comply with the U.N. arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. economic sanctions, imposed on Iraq after its 1990
invasion of Kuwait, will not be lifted until the U.N. arms
inspectors certify that Iraq's weapons of mass destruction have
been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers will seek ways of restoring Arab
reconciliation and solidarity.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the meeting, Arab foreign ministers conducted
extensive consultations to try to work out a statement which will
spell out unified Arab policies towards the Iraqi issue.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf called Saturday
on the Arab countries to condemn the U.S.-British attack on Iraq
and support Baghdad's demand for the lifting of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
But Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said Saturday that
Arab countries would not agree to defy U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
A draft statement for the foreign ministers' meeting proposed
that the Arab countries express sympathy for the plight of the
Iraqi people under the crippling trade embargo.
</P>
<P>
But it will stop short of voicing support for the government of
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein. It will also urge Iraq to fully
abide by the U.N. resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
