<HEADLINE> Highway Construction Boosts Growth of Jiangsu's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Highway construction added 3.2
billion yuan in gross domestic product (GDP) to east China's
Jiangsu Province in 1998, according to a local source.
</P>
<P>
Investment for highway construction reached 14.66 billion
yuan, up 37 percent from 1997. Jiangsu's expressways stretch for
402 kilometers, with another eight expressways, of 906 km long in
total, still being built. High-grade highways are 7,875 km long.
</P>
<P>
Work is going on smoothly on two bridges over the Yangtze
river in Nanjing and Jiangyin, local officials said, adding that
all villages will have access to highways next year.
</P>
<P>
Highway construction cost 200,000 tons of steel, 3.2 million
tons of cement, 100,000 cubic meters of timber, 60,000 tons of
asphalt, and 320,000 tons of petroleum, bringing a boost to
related industries.
</P>
<P>
An average of 95,000 people were working on the site monthly.
Highways construction provided 260,000 job opportunities last
year, statistics show.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
