<HEADLINE> 18 People Killed in Revenge War in South African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Eleven people were killed
and seven wounded last night in Richmond, about 150 km west of
Durban, hours after the assassination of Sifiso Nkabinde, National
Secretary of the United Democratic Movement, police confirmed
Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
"We have been told of the massacre... Police are
investigating," senior superintendent Henry Budhram said.
</P>
<P>
Among those wounded was Mamkhize Ndabazitha, Deputy Chairperson
of the ruling African National Congress (ANC) in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
The attack came less than 12 hours after the assassination of
controversial politician Nkabinde in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
The 38-year old former African National Congress leader in the
Midlands, KuaZulu Natal Province, was gunned down by three unknown
men early Saturday morning. His bodyguard, Simphiwe Dlamini, and
Dlamini's mother, Lendele were injured in the shooting.
</P>
<P>
Richmond residents, who have seen violent activities in the
area for years, believe that Nkabinde's death could spark the
resurgence of violence in the region.
</P>
<P>
So far, police can not confirm whether the Saturday night
massacre was in revenge of Nkabinde's killing. 
</P>
