<HEADLINE> Unseeded Enqvist Upsets Philippoussis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Sweden's Thomas Enqvist upset
14th seed Mark Philippoussis of Australia at the Australian Open
tennis tournament in Melbourne on Sunday to oust another seed at
the Grand Slam opening event.
</P>
<P>
The unseeded Enqvist followed up his elimination of U.S. Open
champion Pat Rafter in the third round with a 6-2, 6-4, 6-7
(3-7), 4-6, 6-2 victory over Philippoussis in two hours 51
minutes.
</P>
<P>
Enqvist will meet with unseeded Swiss Marc Rosset on Tuesday's
quarterfinal, his second following his loss as the seventh seed
to Australian Mark Woodforde in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Philippoussis looked headed for a quick defeat but he rallied
and broke the Swede when he was serving for the match at 5-4 in
the third set.
</P>
<P>
The set went into a tie-breaker which went to a resurgent
Philippoussis 7-3 as Enqvist began to make many errors.
</P>
<P>
With his confidence up, Philippoussis broke his opponent's
service in the ninth game when Enqvist's forehand found the net.
</P>
<P>
Enqvist then broke his serve in the sixth game when on break
point the Australian went for a big wide service only to
double-fault and give the Swede a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
Enqvist made full use of his reprieve and held his service for
5-2 and broke Philipoussis again in the eighth game for his
hard-earned victory.
</P>
<P>
Only four men's seeds -- Andre Agassi (5), Karol Kucera (7),
Yevgeny Kafelnikov (10) and Todd Martin (15) -- qualified for the
quarter-finals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
