<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TV Shopping Brings Moans From Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Television shopping has come
under fire from the public in China's Fujian province for its
high prices, false claims and shoddy products on sale.
</P>
<P>
A survey by the provincial consumers' commission concluded
from an analysis of 19,000 complaints that TV shopping, a
relatively new way for people to buy commodities, has resulted in
many complaints from consumers.
</P>
<P>
TV shopping took off after direct sales were banned and has
appeared on most stations in Fujian. A dozen TV stations in
Fuzhou City alone have set up TV shopping corporations.
</P>
<P>
But many of the prices are too high price, while some
advertisements exaggerated the worth of the products on sale, and
other products are fakes or shoddy, according to a commission
official, who also claimed that many of the companies did not
provide after-sale services.
</P>
<P>
For example, a box of slimming medicine promised it could
reduce weight between three to six kilograms and that this was a
one-off for life. But a customer complained that his weight
actually increased three kilograms. In consultation with the
company selling the product he was told to take more, but his
weight went up another three kilograms after he took three more
doses.
</P>
<P>
Now Fujian Provincial Administration for Industry and Commerce
is enforcing a supervisory code for the industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990124.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Govt Urged to Relax Bank Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Economists and businessmen
attending a meeting of the Thai Chamber of Commerce on Sunday
called on the government to relax bank rules.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda told the participants
that he would press the banks not to take advantage of depositors
by keeping deposit rates low.
</P>
<P>
The interest rates must reflect the cost and income of banks,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Bank clients have complained that banks have been charging high
penalty rates for customers who have defaulted on interest
payment. Tarrin admitted that the new classified non-performing
loans (NPLs), deriving from three-month interest default, are
still on the rise.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin expressed sympathy for borrowers who had been charged
penalty rates after failing to pay interest for three consecutive
months, and said the banks should consider cutting interest rates
for customers instead of punishing them.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that the Bank of Thailand (central bank) has
been asked to consult with banks on the matter, and the outcome is
expected shortly. Tarrin also said he had asked the central bank,
other government-owned banks and commercial banks to speed up debt
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin reiterated the government's plan to launch an additional
economic-stimulus package through increases in fiscal spendings by
March and promised to put more pressure on banks to cut interest
rates further.
</P>
<P>
"The government will initiate a second fiscal package to
stimulate the economy through job-creation projects in both urban
communities and rural areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
Public expenditure aims to create employment opportunities,
educational programs and health care, he said, adding that funds
would be allocated quickly for small projects nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Chalongphob Sussangkarn, president of the Thailand Development
Research Institute, said the government and the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) should re-examine the financial restructuring
program in order to give more flexibility to banks and encourage
them to lend to the "real" economic sector.
</P>
<P>
"The serious question now is to ask whether we should
reconsider the previous measures that were aimed at raising local
bank practices to international standards, given the unresolved
liquidity crunch and the domino threat on bankruptcies of private
companies," he said.
</P>
<P>
Such international standards, like provisions for overdue
interest payment of more than three months, will cause problems
for banks, he said.
</P>
<P>
He estimated that the NPL had surged to about 50 percent, which
would further weaken the lending capacity of the banks.
</P>
<P>
Chalongphob believed the IMF might want to discuss this new
issue given its previous agreement to allow the government to run
a higher budget deficit and go for lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Narong Chokwatana, president of Pan Group, shared Chalongphob's
view by calling upon the government to abolish the economic-reform
program prescribed by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
He took an opposing view to that of Tarrin by saying that banks
should cut interest rates for good customers rather than
non-paying customers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
