<HEADLINE> Iran Seeks U.S. Compensation for Stray Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Iran will seek compensation from
the United States for the losses caused by the strike of two
U.S. stray missiles on Iranian city during the U.S.-British
military attacks on Iraq last month, local daily Tehran times
revealed on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
An Iranian Foreign Ministry official told the daily that Iran
is assessing the damages inflicted on Khorramshahr, southwestern
Khuzestan province and would lodge its complaint against the
U.S. following the assessment.
</P>
<P>
"The assessment of the damages is under consideration," the
official said on the condition of anonymity, "Iran hold the
governments of the U.S and Britain responsible for the damages
caused by the missiles."
</P>
<P>
Khorramshahr was hit by two stray missiles on December 17
when the U.S. and Britain started their military strikes on
Iraq. The missile attacks left heavy damages in the city close
to the Iraqi border but caused no casualty.
</P>
<P>
Iran lodged its strong protest to the U.S. and Britain soon
after the attacks by summoning the British charge d'affaires and
the Swiss ambassador, whose country looks after the American
interests in Iran.
</P>
<P>
However, British Foreign Office Minister Derek Fatchett on
Thursday turned down the Iranian request for compensation for
the missile attacks, because the British forces did not fire
any missiles during the attacks on Iraq last month.
</P>
<P>
In a written reply to the parliament, Fatchett confirmed that
Britain has received a compensation request from the Iranian
government. He suggested that the issue should be raised with the
U.S. authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
