<HEADLINE> Sichuan Helps Jobless Back to Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Sichuan
Province had cut the number of laid-off workers by 10.8 percent
by the end of 1998, against its 1997 figures, local authorities
have said.
</P>
<P>
The success was attributed to the local government's
intensified efforts on re-employment and relevant training.
Statistics show that 678,200 people joined re-employment
projects, and 322,000 laid-off workers of state-owned enterprises
found new jobs last year.
</P>
<P>
The effort will help ensure social stability and boost the
local economy, officials said.
</P>
<P>
In the past year, the provincial government has implemented a
series of preferential policies to encourage re-employment of the
jobless, including speeding up the construction of basic
facilities and exploiting labor-intensive industries to increase
job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
All state-owned enterprises have set up special re-employment
centers, with the total number reaching nearly 7,000. 
</P>
