ROME -- Italian Prime Minster Massimo D'Alema said here on
Friday that Italy's role in the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) "has significantly changed" since the end of
the Cold War, which was a clear turning point for NATO.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the International Herald Tribune, D'Alema
said that in NATO, "Italy is a front-line state with vital
interests on the immediate periphery of the alliance's core
area." He also stressed the need for a direct link between NATO
and the European Union (EU), "to be achieved through a gradual
integration of the Western European Union (WEU) into the EU
structure." (Italy-NATO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- Albania would like to see a political solution to
the Kosovo crisis, a senior Albanian official said Friday, hoping
that the solution will show respect to the will of the ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an international conference in Athens on the
developments in Kosovo, Secretary of State for European
Integration Maqo Lakror said, "We will continue to encourage co
mpatriots in Kosovo to intensify their efforts to adopt a unique
attitude in the frame work of a political process. We are
interested in their cohesion and political solution." The
conference, organized by the Greek Foundation on European and
Foreign Policy, is reportedly held to seek strategies and options
for a peaceful solution to the Kosovo crisis, which saw a tension
triggered by alleged massacre in Recak. (Albania-Kosovo)
</P>
