<HEADLINE> Millennium Disaster Expected Twice in Kenya in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenyans have to brace for two
computer breakdowns this year ahead of the final and devastating
assault on computers by the millennium bug, experts have warned.
</P>
<P>
The first break down is expected at the stroke of midnight of
April 19, 1999, according to a report from the local Herald
newspaper Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The next such breakdown is anticipated on September 9, 1999, a
date when digitalized as 9-9-1999, the four nines will mean
changing commands in computers, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Experts said when the bug strikes in non-compliant instruments,
major facilities like elevators, aircraft, banking, security
operation and virtually any computer-related instrument will
collapse overnight, precipitating what is believed to be record
breaking lawsuits from complaining users.
</P>
<P>
The threat of concerning computer systems has triggered a
massive race to ensure that firms are 2,000 compliant and avert
what could become a " dooms day."
</P>
<P>
For the ordinary Kenyans, running a bank account or those with
an insurance policy with an insurance company, consolation may
only come when one insists on being provided with monthly
statements being issued on the state of accounts to provide a
fall-back position to rely on, when computers go under.
</P>
<P>
And to counter the devastation expected, Kenya has put in place
systems that reject non-compliant computers being imported into
the east African country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
