<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Reports Record Gold Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region produced 10 tons of gold in 1998, a
record high in the region's gold production history.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 gold output ranked the region ninth in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the gold output value was worth
more than 500 million yuan (60.2 million U.S. dollars) and the
region raked in 69.98 million yuan (8.4 million U.S. dollars) in
pre-tax profits.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang is one of the areas that abound in gold reserves in
China and has a prospective gold reserve of 500 tons.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the region's gold production sector faced a number
of difficulties, including two gold price cuts, and with many
gold mines suffering from inadequate availability of gold r
eserves.
</P>
<P>
Local gold administrative departments took measures to help
gold producers lower production costs and encourage them to pool
fund for prospecting gold and increasing availability of gold
reserves, while stepping up efforts to deal with illegal gold
diggers.
</P>
<P>
The region was added with 11.2 tons of verified recoverable
industrial gold reserves last year, said the sources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
