<HEADLINE> Guangzhou to Boost Infrastructure Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, capital of south
China's Guangdong Province, plans to invest 17.1 billion yuan
(2.06 billion U.S. dollars) in infrastructure construction during
1999, up 21 percent on 1998.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of funds will be earmarked for key urban engineering
and communications projects designed to transform Guangzhou into
a modern city, according to Mayor Lin Shusen.
</P>
<P>
Major projects will include completion of a subway line and
construction of several highways and roads, as well as a sewage
treatment plant and the addition of urban landscaped areas
covering 100 hectares.
</P>
<P>
The city spent 14 billion yuan in 1998 on wide-ranging
projects related to communications, sport and cultural
facilities, afforestation and environmental protection. Last
year's allocations were the largest in the past 50 years, said
Lin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
