<HEADLINE> Film-Shooting Begins To Drop In Los Angeles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Film-shooting on the
streets of Los Angeles dipped sharply last year as tighter
spending sliced into film, TV and commercial production.
</P>
<P>
The numbers released Saturday by Entertainment Industry
Development Corp., which issues permits for about 80 percent of
the shooting done in Los Angeles County, show an overall drop of
four percent in production days.
</P>
<P>
Feature film shooting, for example, took a sharp 13 percent
drop as studios cut their bloated movie slates. Commercials, hurt
by the Asian and international economic troubles, fell by 7.5
percent, while television dropped by 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
That marks the strongest statistical evidence to date that the
soaring production growth Southern California enjoyed in the mid
-1990s reached a plateau in the middle of last year.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the production days soared nearly 30 percent
following a 27-percent increase in 1995. The first drop in growth
alarmed industrial experts and economists.
</P>
<P>
Given the increasingly larger role entertainment is playing in
the Southern California economy, they believe that the dip in
production is not only an unwelcome development for the
entertainment industry, but also for the region as a whole
because thousands of small to medium-size suppliers and service
companies do business with Hollywood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
