<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning to Monitor Enterprises' Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province, a major heavy industrial base, has been constructing an
electronic network to monitor production and marketing of 288
large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises in the province.
</P>
<P>
According to local authorities, when the network is put into
operation, the enterprises are requested to list 35 monthly
indexes regarding production and marketing of the respective
enterprises so that relevant departments of the province can
easily refer to and work out policies accordingly.
</P>
<P>
The network is financed by the provincial and city-level
committees of economy and trade at a cost of 120,000 yuan. It is
built on a similar but small existing facility set up last year
and covering 60 businesses.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has one tenth of China's large and medium-sized
enterprises.  And reducing losses and increasing profits in the
enterprises have been listed as a priority of the province's work
agenda.
</P>
<P>
A total of 130 enterprises of the 288 have incurred economic
losses. A local official said the establishment of the
monitoring network would be important for the work of reducing
the losses and increasing profits.
</P>
<P>
Preparations for opening website addresses of different cities
have been finished. It is expected that the 288 enterprises will
also be hooked into the new electronic network before the
traditional spring festival which falls on February 16.  
</P>
</TEXT>
