<HEADLINE> African Traditional Dress Urged to Be Promoted in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Managing Director of the
Harare-based Queen of Africa Boutique, Dulce Ricardo, has launched
a campaign to promote the wearing of African fashion by African
women, The Sunday Mail magazine reported.
</P>
<P>
The rapid permeation of westernized clothing and accessories in
the continent have virtually sidelined traditional African
outfits, especially in young ladies, Ricardo told the magazine
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
She said this westernization of fashion has resulted in a loss
of identity, recognition and pride.
</P>
<P>
"It is now very difficult to separate Africans from Americans
and Europeans, because we are all wearing the same things," she
said.
</P>
<P>
"What Queen of Africa Boutique is campaigning for now is the
adoption of traditional outfits instead of western ones," Ricardo
said.
</P>
<P>
She said that some of the continent's greatest women have worn
traditional clothing, such as Zimbabwe's first lady Grace Mugabe,
and their identifies and cultures have therefore been respected as
they radiate from the very clothes that they have worn.
</P>
<P>
"Perhaps the best-dressed women in any social and formal
gathering would be those wearing African dresses, which are
outstanding and adaptable to any setting," said Ricardo.
</P>
<P>
Apart from their eye-catching, glittering appearance, African
dresses are weather-resistant, thus providing warmth in cold, and
are cool during heat, she said.
</P>
<P>
"I hope we will go into the next millennium holding closely
onto our identity, or culture and our pride. We must begin the
African renaissance from our very clothes," Ricardo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
