<HEADLINE> US to Spend More Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANAHEIM, California, January 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice
President Al Gore is expected to announce Sunday that the White
House will increase spending on high-tech projects next year at
the annual meeting of the American Association for the
Advancement of Science in Anaheim, a report from Washington D.C.
said.
</P>
<P>
The administration plans to spend 366 million dollars more on
high-tech projects during fiscal 2000, which starts on Oct. 1,
and extend a research tax credit of 2.4 billion dollars aimed at
helping scientists develop super-fast computers that can speak
and understand language, AP quoted a senior administration
official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The spending increases are part of the administration's
1.8-billion-dollar budget for high-tech research, about 60 perc
ent of which will go to research universities, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Gore also will propose extending an existing tax credit worth
2.4 billion dollars, which offers a 20-percent tax break based on
a company's increase in research spending. 
</P>
</TEXT>
