<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0520 GMT, January 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM -- Leaders of the Great Lakes region Saturday
suspended the economic sanctions imposed on Burundi since August
1996 when Pierre Buyoya came to power in a bloodless military
coup.
</P>
<P>
President Yoweri Museveni of Uganda, chairman of the one-day
summit attended by seven east and central African presidents or
their representatives, announced the decision in Tanzania's
northern town of Arusha. (Burundi-Economic Sanction)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thailand is to propose the setting up of a regional
mechanism to deal with labor migration in Asia when it hosts a
meeting on the issue in April, the Bangkok Post reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Worked out by government officials, non-government
organizations and academics, the proposal calls for member states
of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) to launch
the mechanism before extending it to other Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh, one of the main countries of origin of migrant
labor, was identified as a target member. (Thailand-Labor
Migration)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA (Xinhua) -- Colombian international
reserves reached 8.737 billion U.S. dollars on January 15, a
10.95 percent drop from 9.812 billion dollars one year ago.
</P>
<P>
The fall in last year's international reserves attributed by
the e national bank to its efforts of stabilizing its currency
and the exchange rate. (Colombia-International Reserves)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentine President Carlos Menem said Saturday
that his proposal to adopt the U.S. dollar as the national
currency accords with the United States plan to create a free
trade zone throughout the Americas.
</P>
<P>
"We need a single currency for Mercosur, and this process of
economic integration into a free trade zone in all of the
continent has as a logical consequence the possibility of a
single currency," Menem told a press conference. Mercosur groups
Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay to form a top trade bloc
in South America. (Argentina-Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil will give preference to internal tourism to
create jobs and reduce the exit of hard currency, Caio Carvalho,
Brazilian Tourism Company president, said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the change in the parity between the U.S. dollar
and the local currency, the real, has been good for domestic
tourism, which costs less than going abroad.
</P>
<P>
The value of the real against the dollar has fallen
significantly since the Brazilian government allowed the floating
of the currency this month. (Brazil-Tourism)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- China's foreign trade administration system will be
radically transformed, the Business Weekly reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
China is to establish a foreign trade system based on tools
such as tariffs, taxation and credits, said Wang Shichun, deputy
director-general of the foreign trade administration department
of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation
(MOFTEC). (China-Trade System-Reform) 
</P>
</TEXT>
