<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, India to Hold Talks on Bus Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- India has agreed to sign an
agreement with Bangladesh on introduction of bus service between
their capitals for the convenience of travelers, the Independent
newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Indian government had invited an official delegation from
Dhaka to hold pre-agreement talks on February 3-5 in New Delhi,
the newspaper quoted Foreign Secretary Mustafizur Rahman as
saying.
</P>
<P>
An official delegation at the level of secretary or joint
secretary would go to India for signing the deal, he said, hoping
that bus service between Dhaka and Calcutta would start sometime
in February.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed Dhaka-Delhi bus-service agreement, buses
would run from Dhaka to Calcutta and passengers are also free to
travel by bus onward to New Delhi or any parts of India.
</P>
<P>
He said schedules of departure and arrival of buses would
strictly be maintained while the Bangladesh Rifles and the Indian
Border Security Forces would open the designated entry points on
the border accordingly.
</P>
<P>
Commuter buses should stop at least at two points between
Benapole and Dhaka while proper resthouse facilities along the
route would be arranged under the agreement. 
</P>
