<HEADLINE> Pope Sets out Church's Goals for New Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Pope John Paul II has
signed here a major document setting out the Catholic church's
goals for the new millennium and the actions to be taken.
</P>
<P>
The document, made known by the Pope at a mass Saturday,
touches upon human rights, indigenous peoples, globalization,
foreign debt, corruption, drug trafficking and the environment.
</P>
<P>
The document called drug trafficking a serious threat for the
social fabric of the nations of America, saying it contributes to
the increase of crimes, violence, and destruction of families
while destroying governments, eroding the economic security and
the stability of the nations.
</P>
<P>
The document stressed drug trafficking as one of the most
urgent challenges which many nations of the world must face.
</P>
<P>
Turning to globalization, the document said, globalization can
have positive consequences, such as promotion of efficiency and
increase of production that permit the development of the
relations between the diverse countries and strengthen the unity
of the peoples.
</P>
<P>
However, it warned that if globalization follows the mere laws
of the market applied "according to the conveniences of the
powerful," it also has negative consequences.
</P>
<P>
The Pope repeated in the document that the globalized economy
must be examined in the "light of the principles of social
justice."
</P>
<P>
The 24-page message was written in response to suggestions
from bishops in both North and South America, called to the
Vatican in 1997 to agree on joint strategy to win back disenc
hanted Catholics and promote a genuine "Christian spirituality."
</P>
<P>
The Pope arrived here on Friday at the start of a trip which
will on Tuesday take him to St. Louis, Missouri. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
