<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Administration System To Be Reformed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- China's foreign trade
administration system will be radically transformed, the Business
Weekly reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
China is to establish a foreign trade system based on tools
such as tariffs, taxation and credits, said Wang Shichun, deputy
director-general of the foreign trade administration department
of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation
(MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
China needs an import and export license control mechanism
and rational and transparent quota allocation procedures to help
foster the competitiveness of the Chinese economy, according to
Wang.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC has cut the number of licensed exports to 58 at the
beginning of this year, he said, adding that the number will be
further reduced.
</P>
<P>
Instead of being monopolized by State export firms, quotas
will be allocated via public bidding among Chinese exporters and
determined by higher prices, the deputy director-general noted.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, 20 private manufacturers were granted
import and export rights. Wang described it as another major move
in trade system reform.
</P>
<P>
In addition, some 6,000 major Chinese manufacturers no longer
need MOFTEC approval to conduct foreign trade after they register
with relevant authorities.
</P>
<P>
Wang pointed out that his department will gradually shift its
focus from the arduous task of daily examination and approval, to
market research, policy-making and negotiations to forestall
trade disputes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
