<DOCNO> XIE19990124.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Menem Defends Plan to "Dollarize" Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President
Carlos Menem said Saturday that his proposal to adopt the U.S.
dollar as the national currency accords with the United States
plan to create a free trade zone throughout the Americas.
</P>
<P>
"We need a single currency for Mercosur, and this process of
economic integration into a free trade zone in all of the
continent has as a logical consequence the possibility of a
single currency," Menem told a press conference. Mercosur groups
Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay to form a top trade bloc
in South America.
</P>
<P>
Menem, who was in La Rioja, his home province, was responding
to the nation's main opposition Alliance, which had questioned
the plan of "dollarizing" the Argentine economy as a protection
from the crisis that affects neighboring Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Raul Alfonsin, former Argentine president and one of the
Alliance's main leaders, had said that to adopt the dollar as the
national currency would mean subjecting the country to U.S.
decisions.
</P>
<P>
"We are losing our nation's ability to take decisions. In all
areas we are putting the country's future in jeopardy," Alfonsin
said Thursday after hearing the proposal.
</P>
<P>
In defending the plan, Menem said: "It is stupid to say that
to use the dollar as the national currency is to attack the
sovereignty. With that criterion in Europe all the countries
which adopted the euro as their currency have attacked their own
sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
Menem's proposal of adopting the dollar to replace the peso,
for which Argentina and the United States would have to reach an
agreement, has provoked criticism from some politicians and
economists. There were accusations that the proposal was just
the sort of "audacious" move in the election year of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Argentina pegged the Peso at par with the dollar in 1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
