<HEADLINE> Thailand Wants Regional Mechanism for Labor Migration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is to propose the
setting up of a regional mechanism to deal with labor migration in
Asia when it hosts a meeting on the issue in April, the Bangkok
Post reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Worked out by government officials, non-government
organizations and academics, the proposal calls for member states
of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) to launch
the mechanism before extending it to other Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh, one of the main countries of origin of migrant
labor, was identified as a target member.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was forged during a day-long brainstorming session
in preparation for the international symposium towards regional
cooperation on undocumented migration, which Bangkok is due to
host from April 21-23.
</P>
<P>
A total of 18 countries are due to participate in the symposium
including the nine member states of ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
A official from the Thai foreign Ministry was quoted as saying
that countries of origin should prevent migration problems by
looking after their nationals and providing information on
international law.
</P>
<P>
When a problem occurs, they should take them back and the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees and other
international organizations should help in the repatriation of
these migrants, the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
