<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AmCham-China White Paper Praises China's Commercial Surrounding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- More than 550 U.S.-based
companies doing business in China recently agreed that the
context surrounding American commercial involvement in China was
"largely positive", the English Business Weekly reported today.
</P>
<P>
This was announced in the first white paper issued by the
American Chamber of Commerce in China (AmCham-China), which is on
behalf of over 1,250 corporate and individual members.
</P>
<P>
In the white paper, the chamber recognized China's
implementation of market-oriented reforms and the achievement of
high economic growth rates consistently since 1979. "Especially
noteworthy has been China's stability and continued growth in the
face of recent Asian financial troubles," it said.
</P>
<P>
Serving as a forum for the collective voice of American
businesses in China, the white paper also cited three major
stumbling blocks for U.S. businesses in China which were the
growing U.S. trade deficit with China, the uncertainty regarding
China's Normal Trade Relations status, and the controversy
surrounding China's accession to the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
"American commercial diplomatic efforts should be expanded
through increased funding for trade advocacy, trade finance and
on-the-ground commercial support," the white paper said.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. Government should also remove unilateral sanctions,
such as restrictions on the ability of the Trade and Development
Agency and the U.S. Agency for International Development to
operate in China."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it also encouraged the US Government to extend
permanent NTR trading status to China.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, member companies of the chamber also raised a series
of suggestions to the Chinese Government, such as increasing the
transparency of rules and regulations, opening the distribution
services sector, and strengthening local enforcement of laws and
regulations concerning intellectual property rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
