<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Currency Devaluation No Terrible Harm to China: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian financial turbulence
will not do terrible harm to China's foreign trade sector, the
"Business Weekly" reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Li Zhixiang, a senior researcher from the Chinese Academy of
International Trade and Economic Cooperation, told the newspaper
that the devaluation of the real will only have limited influence
on China.
</P>
<P>
China's exports to Brazil reached 959 million U.S. dollars
between January and November last year, only accounting for 0.5
percent of China's total exports in the period.
</P>
<P>
"The whole Latin American area accounts for a mere 1.6 percent
of China's total export volume," said Li. "Therefore the losses
caused by the currency devaluation in this region will not amount
to a significant level."
</P>
<P>
The researcher said that the growth rate of China's exports to
Brazil tumbled from a hefty 36.8 percent in 1997 to a negative
1.7 percent at the end of last year as a result of weak demand
and new import barriers erected by the country.
</P>
<P>
Trade protectionism has grown in Latin America since it was
hit by the repercussions of the Asian financial turmoil last year.
</P>
<P>
Martin Posth, vice-chairman of the Asia Pacific Advisory
Council of U.S.-based Arthur D. Little International INC, told Bus
iness Weekly that he believes the Brazilian turbulence would not
spread to Hong Kong Special Administrative Region and China's
mainland.
</P>
<P>
But some analysts said that in the long run, the Brazilian
turmoil may hurt overseas investors' confidence in the renminbi
and the Hong Kong dollar.
</P>
<P>
"The Brazilian monetary and economic crisis will cause bankers
and portfolio investors to reassess the risks involved in
investing in all emerging markets, and therefore may make it a
little more difficult for these economies, including China, to
raise capital from the international financial market," said Mu
Yibin, a scholar from the People's Bank of China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
