<HEADLINE> Compensation Call for UK Olympic Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- A leading member of Britain's
failed bid to stage the 2000 Olympic Games said on Saturday
Manchester should be compensated for the millions of pounds it
spent on its fruitless campaign.
</P>
<P>
Labour MP Graham Stringer made the call as Sydney faced more
allegations of corruption over its winning bid.
</P>
<P>
Further allegations are being made of favours being granted to
IOC members and jobs for their relatives during the battle for
the games.
</P>
<P>
Stringer, MP for Manchester Blackley, who was leader of the
city council and a key member of the bid team, said the IOC
should compensate all the losing cities.
</P>
<P>
"They paid out good money and they should be paid
compensation," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The IOC have sat back and done nothing when they were in a
position to clean the whole thing up."
</P>
<P>
Manchester was estimated to have spent 7.5 million pounds of
private sector money on its bid.
</P>
<P>
Stringer said he suspected it was impractical to take the
games away from Sydney at such a late stage. But the IOC should
consider fining or punishing them if they had behaved improperly.
</P>
<P>
"You only have to be within the confines of the Olympic
movement for five minutes to realise that things are not
straightforward, that there has been corruption," he said.
</P>
<P>
"That doesn't mean you can prove it. What has happened
recently is that proof has come out that Salt Lake City and
Sydney used bribery and improper practices to get their
nominations.
</P>
<P>
"We always said we were a clean bid and were not indulging in
bribery and we thought that was a positive asset. We have played
by the rules.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know if we would have won. There were other
geophysical reasons involved. But we will never know," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
