<HEADLINE> China Opening Karst Cave Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, January 24 (Xinhua) -- China plans to build a karst
cave museum beside Yaolin Fairyland, a group of karst caves in
Zhejiang Province, this year.
</P>
<P>
The Yaolin Karst Cave Museum will be a part of the Fairyland
for use in karst topography research and as a tourist attraction.
It will have pictures, cave models, relics, and multimedia
technology for shows on the formation, features, culture and
protection of karst caves.
</P>
<P>
Yaolin Fairyland is in Tonglu County, about 100 km. west of
Hangzhou, Zhejiang's capital. It has 6 major caves, the largest
of which covers a 27,000-sq.m. area.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say the caves are typical of the karst topography
of a damp subtropical coastal area. They were opened to the
outside world in 1980 and have had more than 15 million
visitors.
</P>
<P>
The Fourth International Conference on Tourist Caves is
scheduled to meet in Yaolin in October 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
