<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sanctions Suspended to Encourage Burundi Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Great
Lakes region Saturday suspended the economic sanctions imposed on
Burundi since August 1996 when Pierre Buyoya came to power in a
bloodless military coup.
</P>
<P>
President Yoweri Museveni of Uganda, chairman of the one-day
summit attended by seven east and central African presidents or
their representatives, announced the decision in Tanzania's
northern town of Arusha.
</P>
<P>
Following a briefing by the international mediator, Tanzania's
former president Julius Nyerere, Museveni said the on-going peace
process in Burundi, however, will be closely monitored "until the
sanctions are completely lifted."
</P>
<P>
At the summit, President Pierre Buyoya of Burundi pledged
continuation of the peace talks which have entered the fourth
round since last June under Nyerere's mediation because they are
"a sacred and an irreversible process."
</P>
<P>
He urged all Burundians to join the peace process to restore
the country to the path of development and reconstruction although
it will take many years and dismissed fears that his government
was not sincere to restore democracy.
</P>
<P>
However, Buyoya expressed his concern over the continuing armed
 hostilities launched by the armed Hutu rebels.
</P>
<P>
Museveni assured Buyoya that the region was committed to see
peace restored in Burundi, underlining that "few extremists
(referring to armed rebels) should not stop us from negotiations."
</P>
<P>
Museveni, Buyoya and their Tanzanian, Kenyan, Rwandan
counterparts and representatives of presidents of Ethiopia, Zambia
and the Democratic Republic of Congo as well as the Organization
of African Unity (OAU) Secretary General Salim Ahmed Salim
expressed their thanks to Nyerere for his mediation effort.
</P>
<P>
President Daniel arap Moi of Kenya, an elderly east African
leader, urged Africa to move away from crisis to development and
economic progress.
</P>
<P>
"When will that dream of the United States of Africa come
true?" Moi asked his counterparts.
</P>
<P>
He said small countries like Burundi should join in the
regional grouping of economic and political cooperation to bring
prosperity to their people who have been shattered by poverty,
ignorance and under-development.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the fourth round of talks on Burundi peace process
concluded in Arusha late Saturday with Nyerere calling for
stepping up the efforts to reach an early peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Encouraged by the suspension of the sanctions on Burundi,
Nyerere suggested at the closing of the plenary session, held at
the Arusha International Conference Center, that when the talks
resume in June, the parties should be ready to sign a peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
He said the four committees formed during the talks should be
ready to present their reports in June in a bid to "enable all of
us to reach an agreement."
</P>
<P>
The committees fall into four groups on the nature of Burundi
conflict, good governance and democracy, peace and security as
well as economic reconstruction and development of Burundi.
</P>
</TEXT>
